        <h2>London and Paris Trip</h2>

        <h3>Wednesday, June 25</h3>
<p>We got to London's Heathrow Airport around 10:30 AM their time (so about 5:30am EST). It was nice to finally get off the plane since we were stuck on it FOREVER.</p>
<p>Oh well.</p>
<p>We wandered around the airport for a while. It was HUGE! (sorry Billy Fuccillo) The one we left from in Ottawa had seven terminals, this one must have seven hundred.</p>
<p>We finally found the Undergound station after Many moving floors and escalators.</p>
<p>Our hotel was on Queensborgh Terrance near Bayswater street.</p>
<p>We got there around one (we were on the Underground hopelessly lost for a while) and checked in. Allison and I are in room 707. </p>
<p>We took a nap since we both had major jet lag (you try sleeping on that plane). Around 3, we left to go out into London.</p>
<p>We caught a red doubledecker bus a couple of blocks down the street and took it to around Oxford Street. I was having a good time seeing all the Mini Coopers, Audi TTs, Smart Cars, and any other cute looking car. :)</p>
<p>Well, we got off the bus and wandered around for a while. I saw a Swatch store and a sock store. Swatch!!!!</p>
<p>Allison wanted to go see Chitty Chitty Bang Bang that was playing in the Pallidium. We walked down into theatre district and found a tickets place.</p>
<p>Allison's dad wanted to see some other play then another.</p>
<p>Finally we bought tickets for My Fair Lady. Allison wanted to see it before it closed.</p>
<p>We then ate dinner at a pub place. I had Taco's no I had Nacho's (I was distracted by the tv). After we ate we wandered around the place we were in, I'm not sure what it was called but there was a lot of theaters.</p>
<p>We finally found the theater iit was in the Theatre Royal on Drury Lane.</p>
<p>We sat in the upper circle. The theater was a real one, with boxes and a balcony and fancy salons and staircases. The play was really good and I liked it. Afterwards we wandered around some more and made it back to the hotel.</p>
<h3>Thursday, June 26</h3>
<p>We had breakfast at the hotel and left for the British Museum. We wandered around looking for it for a while and then eventually did.</p>
<p>It's a huge museum, huge! The grand court was entirely made out of marble.</p>
<p>We went into the Egypt exhibit (the museum was free, all national museums are here, the lottery pays for it) and there were masses of small schoolchildren.</p>
<p>The Rosetta Stone was there and a bunch of other Egyptian stuff. There was a lot of ancient culture matieral. The entire museum was full of it.</p>
<p>We left soon and wandered down a nearby street. We then had a fight (not really) about what we were going to have for lunch. No one could decide on anything. We ended up at a korean cafe type thing. I got a soda called Fanta.</p>
<p>I LOVE FANTA.</p>
<p>It's a German coca-cola soda that's ike orange-lemon stuff. I don't know. It's really good and I LOVE IT.</p>
<p>Well after that we headed towards Regents Park.</p>
<p>It was about a million degrees out and I had pants on. Allison's parents wanted to see A Midsummer's Ngiht Dream in the open air theatre. We bought tickets, then wandered around and look at the kids in school uniforms that were there.</p>
<p>We got to the theater to see our seats were in the sun. We sat there and watched the first half. Then we left because it was a million degrees out and the play was awful.</p>
<p>We wandered around then took the underground to Oxford Street to do some shopping.</p>
<p>We went back to the hotel and then to a little Indian Buffet. They had really good food!</p>
<h3>Friday June 27</h3>
<p>We had breakfast at the hotel again and then went to exchange some money. Then we went back to the hotel since it had started to rain. As soon as they got coats and umbrellas the rain stopped.</p>
<p>We then took the underground to London Bridge and walked around there for a while. There was another food fight and during that we found The Globe.</p>
<p>Richard III was playing and we got grounding tickets because they were only 5 pounds compared to 25 pounds for sitting tickets (My Fair Lady was 20 pounds).</p>

<p>We finally ate at the cafe at the Globe then waited around for the play to start at 2 o'clock. We stood right next to the right side of the stage so we could have something to lean on.</p>
<p>The play was really good and rather long, but being right next to the stage was interesting. Seeing a play in the Globe was completely different than in another theater.</p>
<p>Audience participation was encouraged but the crowd was shy at first, except for one guy upfront with a beer. He yelled "Kill him!" to Am(??) to kill Richard and the girl playing Richard took his beer and drank some of it.</p>
<p>Another thing was that the entire cast was girls. Instead of an entire cast of men it was an entire cast of women.</p>
<p>Christine the Play Critic gives Richard III at the Globe a 0.92 out of 1. It got boring in some parts but the fighting and good actresses made up for it.</p>
<p>After the Globe, we walked along the Thames some more and the Tate Museum of Modern Art. Allison and I walked through the Modern Galleries of Still Life on the 3rd floor. I saw a painting by Pollock, Cezanne, and Matisse.</p>
<p>Then we hit the gift shop. After that we went to the temmpas (tapas) cafe. I ordered chicken croquet (croquette) and I liked it!<br>
Muha!</p><br>
<p>Afterwards we crossed the Thames on a pedestrian bridge and walked for a bit on the other side of the river. We then caught a bus for Oxford Street and just rode it around looking at everything. There were a lot of pret restaurants and Pizza Huts EVERYWHERE.</p>
<p>We made our way back to the hotel area and went to a nice Italian restaurant on Queensway Street. I had some really good pizza there.</p>
<h3>Saturday June 28</h3>
<p>We had breakfast in the hotel and then we went back to the room to get our dirty clothes so they can be washed. We did so and went with Allison's mom over to Queensway. She took the clothes and Allison and I crossed the street to look into this shop we wanted to look at.</p>
<p>It was closed so we went to look for Allison's mom. We couldn't find the laundry mat so we wandered back up the street to see that the store, Punky Fish, was open.</p>
<p>We went in and looked around. It looked like it was going to be a cheap shop but it wasn't. We crossed the street in disappointment. We went into another store and we were excited to see prices of &pound; 2 and 4.</p>
<p>Allison bought some things and then we went to look for her mom again. We couldn't find her so we went into the mall across the street. We went into some stores then walked up and down the street some more looking for this laundry mat. We went a little further and there it was.</p>
<p>We went back tot he hotel and picked up Allison's dad. Then we took the underground to Notting Hill Gate and headed towards Portabello Road.</p>
<p>We lurked amongst the shops and looked at things. Allison got a T-shirt and I got a change pursey thing. Then we both bought extremely cool Japanese wallets. After walkeding back up Notting Hill we  went to a greek restaurant. I ordered some chicken. I had some calamari too.We then picked up our luggage and called for a taxis to take us to Heathrow.</p>
<p>Unfortunately it wasn't a cool London taxis, but it was a nice black mercedes-benz with black leather. The driver was from Iran and really nice.</p>
